  {
    "index": 3,
    "hash": "6+ozru7jd3JNMvBWiTjcDA2u3U0=",
    "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:45.000Z",
    "action": {
      "type": "SET_CONTENT",
      "input": {
        "content": "## Claim\n\nThe Bee HTTP API exposes WebSocket subscriptions only for PSS, GSOC, and chunk streaming \u2014 **feed updates have no native WS subscription**, so real-time feed watching must be built out of other primitives.\n\n## Evidence\n\nWebSocket endpoints:\n\n| Endpoint                        | Purpose                             |\n|---------------------------------|-------------------------------------|\n| `WS /pss/subscribe/{topic}`     | Stream decrypted PSS messages       |\n| `WS /gsoc/subscribe/{address}`  | Stream GSOC updates                 |\n| `WS /chunks/stream`             | Stream chunk uploads (parallel)     |\n\nOptions for watching feed updates:\n1. **Poll** `GET /feeds/{owner}/{topic}` at intervals (what the adapter does today)\n2. **GSOC notification**: publisher sends a GSOC on update; subscriber polls only on notification\n3. **PSS notification**: same pattern via PSS instead of GSOC\n4. **Advance retrieve requests** (protocol level, not API-exposed): request the next feed index before it exists; the node holds the request until the update arrives \u2014 gives sub-second latency without polling\n\n## Why it matters\n\nExplains why sub-second collaboration latency needs a sidecar notification channel (GSOC or PSS) rather than just a WebSocket on the feed. Also flags \"advance retrieve requests\" as a future path if exposed in bee-js.\n",
        "updatedAt": "2026-05-13T13:00:45.000Z"
      },
      "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:45.000Z"
    }
  },
